\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{iIRF100_numeric_analytic}
    \caption{Numerical solution for $\alpha$ in FaIR v1.3 versus analytic solution in FaIR v2.0. This highlights the reason for the lowered $r_0$ parameter in FaIR v2.0 compared to FaIR v1.3 \citep{Smith2017} or v1.0 \citep{Millar2016}, as we see that for pre-industrial $\alpha$ values (0.12 in v1.0 or 0.16 in v1.3), the analytic solution requires a lower iIRF$_{100}$ than the numeric. Since both solutions are near identical once iIRF$_{100}$ values reach 45 (close to the present-day value), this could lead to FaIR v2.0 systematically simulating lower CO$_2$ concentrations through a lower $\alpha$ than FaIR v1.3 or v1.0. However, this will be compensated to a certain degree by the slight increase in default $r_T$ and $r_u$ parameters.}
\end{figure}
\begin{figure}[H]
